    <h3 id="instructions-and-procedures-3">Instructions and procedures</h3>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>Ensure the <a href="https://linked.data.gov.au/def/nrm/d15d05db-5007-411e-b257-105ef4f76821">Plot Selection and Layout Module</a> has been completed to
mark out the plot boundary and define the current plot and visit in the
Monitor app.</p></li>
</ol>
<ol start="2" type="1">
<li><p>Select Soils Module &gt; Plot soil observation and pit
characterisation protocol.</p></li>
<li><p>Traverse the core plot to familiase yourself with the homogeneity
in respect to landform and soils.</p></li>
<li><p>Locate the site for the soil pit, navigate to outside the
southwest corner of the plot and assess whether the location best
represents the soil of the plot and is a suitable location for the soil
pit. If this is not the case, move to a better representative location
within the plot, taking care not to obstruct other concurrent survey
tasks.</p></li>
<li><p>Select record the soil pit location. The app will automatically
record the soil pit ID, the project and current survey, along with the
location details.</p></li>
</ol>
<h4 class="unnumbered" id="soil-site-observation">Soil site
observation</h4>
<ol start="6" type="1">
<li><p>Record a brief <em>location description</em> (i.e. a general
description to assist with re-location using distances and direction to
landmarks, where the soil site is located in respect to the plot, where
the soil pit is sitting within the context of the landscape, surrounding
vegetation community).</p></li>
<li><p>Consider a 20m radius around the soil pit as the soil site
observation, using the Yellow Book as a reference source, complete
landform and land surface fields:</p></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li><p><em>means of evaluation</em> – select from a dropdown list how
the slope will be measured.</p></li>
<li><p><em>slope -</em> record the percentage. This number should be
between 0 and 90 (see <a href="#measuring-slope">Additional
guidelines</a>).</p></li>
<li><p><em>slope class -</em> automatically generated once the slope
percentage is entered.</p></li>
<li><p><em>morphological type</em> and <em>inclination of slope</em> –
select from dropdown lists.</p></li>
<li><p><em>landform element</em> – select from dropdown list. The
landform element at the soil site observation level may differ from the
plot description landform element.</p></li>
<li><p><em>condition of surface soil when dry</em> – select from
dropdown list.</p></li>
<li><p><em>disturbance</em> – select from dropdown list.</p></li>
</ul>
<ol start="8" type="1">
<li><p>Consider a 20 m radius around the soil pit as the soil site
observation, using the Yellow Book as a reference source, complete land
surface observations. Select the checkbox(s) against the land surface
features that are present at the soil site observation, this will limit
the fields to enter only those that are applicable:</p></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li><p><em>microrelief</em> – relief up to a few metres above the plane
of the land surface. Assess and record <em>microrelief type</em>,
<em>vertical interval distance (m)</em>, <em>horizontal interval
distance (m)</em>, <em>component of microrelief sampled</em>. Record
multiple if present.</p></li>
<li><p><em>erosion</em> – accelerated or induced erosion rather than
natural erosion. Assess and record <em>state of erosion</em>,
<em>erosion type</em> and the <em>erosion severity</em>. Record multiple
if present.</p></li>
<li><p><em>surface coarse fragments</em> – assess and record <em>surface
coarse fragments abundance</em>, <em>size of surface coarse
fragments</em>, <em>shape of surface coarse fragments</em>,
<em>lithology of surface coarse fragments</em>, and <em>strength of
surface coarse fragments</em>. Record multiple if present.</p></li>
<li><p><em>rock outcrop</em> – assess and record <em>rock outcrop
abundance</em> and <em>rock outcrop lithology</em>.</p></li>
</ul>
<ol start="9" type="1">
<li><p>Record any additional observations in the soil site observation
comments.</p></li>
<li><p>Select complete the soil site observations to save and continue
to the soil pit characterisation.</p>
<p>Soil pit characterisation</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Refer to the Yellow Book for further descriptions on all field codes
and descriptions.</p>
<ol start="11" type="1">
<li><p>Record the <em>observation type</em> used to expose the soil
profile.</p></li>
<li><p>Dig a soil pit to 1 m+ deep or to depth of limiting layer. Place
the spoil on a ground sheet to minimise disturbance and assist
backfilling. Record the <em>soil pit depth (m)</em> of the soil pit. See
<a href="#soil-pit-characterisation">Additional guidelines</a>.</p></li>
<li><p>If a depth of 1 m+ cannot be achieved, record what digging was
<em>stopped by</em>.</p></li>
<li><p>Assess which face of the pit is best for photographing, taking
into consideration angle of the sun and shadows. Position the pit tape
on the left or right edge of the best face and select the <em>soil pit
photo</em> button to capture an image using your device's camera.
Alternatively, an external camera can be used to take the photo. See <a href="#soil-pit-characterisation">Additional guidelines</a>.</p></li>
<li><p>Assess and identify the soil horizons in the soil profile. Select
the <em>add soil horizon</em> button to record soil profile data for the
first soil horizon.</p></li>
<li><p>Record the <em>Horizon</em>. Refer to the Soil Profile section in
the Yellow Book and the <a href="#horizons">Additional guidelines</a>
below for further descriptions. A preliminary horizon can be given at
this point and may be edited after the profile is described.</p></li>
<li><p>Record the <em>upper depth (m)</em> and <em>lower depth (m)</em>
of the soil horizon.</p></li>
<li><p>Assess the boundary between the horizon being assessed and the
horizon below, recording <em>boundary distinctness</em> and <em>boundary
shape</em>.</p></li>
<li><p>Assess and record <em>field texture</em>, including the <em>field
texture grade, texture qualification</em> and <em>texture
modifier.</em></p></li>
<li><p>Assess the colour of the soil in the horizon using the Munsell
Soils Color Charts (Munsell Color 2009). Record the <em>moisture
status</em> of the soil and the <em>colour value</em> (e.g. 10YR 4/6 or
hue value/chroma) Moist and dry colours can be recorded (see <a href="#soil-colour">Additional guidelines</a>).</p></li>
<li><p>Select the checkbox(s) against the features that are present in
the horizon, this will limit the fields to enter only those that are
applicable to the horizon:</p></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li><p>mottles – assess and record mottle type, mottle abundance, mottle
size, mottle contrast, mottle colour and distinctness of boundaries.
Record multiple if present.</p></li>
<li><p>coarse fragments – assess and record coarse fragment abundance,
size of coarse fragments, shape of coarse fragments, lithology of coarse
fragments, strength of coarse fragments, alteration of coarse fragments
and distribution of coarse fragments. Record multiple if
present.</p></li>
<li><p>structure – assess and record grade of pedality, size of peds,
type of pedality and compound pedality. Record multiple if present (i.e.
largest peds parting to smaller sized peds down to the primary
ped).</p></li>
<li><p>segregation – assess and record abundance of segregations, nature
of segregations, form of segregations, size of segregations, strength of
segregations and magnetic attributes of segregations. Record multiple if
present.</p></li>
<li><p>voids – assess and record width of cracks, abundance of medium
and coarse macropores, abundance of very fine and fine macropores and
diameter of macropores. Record multiple if present.</p></li>
<li><p>pans – assess and record cementation of pan, type of pan,
continuity of pan and structure of pan.</p></li>
<li><p>cutans – assess and record types of cutans, abundance of cutans
and distinctness of cutans.</p></li>
<li><p>roots - assess and record root abundance and root size.</p></li>
</ul>
<ol start="22" type="1">
<li><p>Assess and record consistence, including soil water status,
strength of soil, stickiness and plasticity type.</p></li>
<li><p>Conduct the following field test on soil collected from the
horizon:</p></li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li><p><em>Effervescence</em> – assess and record the <em>effervescence
of carbonate in fine earth</em> using 2–3 drops of 1 Molar HCl.</p></li>
<li><p>pH – assess and record <em>field pH</em> (to 0.5 of a unit) using
a pH kit based on the specifications of Raupach and Tucker (1959).
Portable pH meters may also be used.</p></li>
<li><p>Electrical conductivity (EC) - assess and record <em>EC 1:5</em>
using a portable EC meter. Follow instructions for the particular meter
being used.</p></li>
</ul>
<ol start="24" type="1">
<li><p>Repeat steps 16 – 23 for each soil horizon down the soil profile,
select the + button to <em>add a new horizon</em>. When all horizons
have been entered, select <em>complete horizons</em>. The app will
display a summary of the horizons to assist with soil
classification.</p></li>
<li><p>Assess and record the <em>Australian Soil Classification</em>
(ASC), including the <em>confidence level</em>, <em>order</em>,
<em>suborder</em>, <em>great group</em>, <em>subgroup</em> and
<em>family</em> level. Refer to the third edition of <em>The Australian
Soil Classification</em> for further descriptions (Isbell and The
National Committee on Soil and Terrain 2021).</p></li>
<li><p>Toggle the <em>ASC needs to be determined back in the lab</em> on
if further laboratory investigation is required to complete
classification.</p></li>
<li><p>Assess and record <em>permeability</em> and <em>drainage</em>
(that would likely occur in most years) of the soil.</p></li>
<li><p>Record the <em>R horizon depth (m)</em> if reached.</p></li>
<li><p>Record any additional <em>soil profile comments</em>.</p></li>
<li><p>Select <em>complete soil pit characterisation</em> to save and
continue to soil sampling.</p></li>
</ol>
<h4 class="unnumbered" id="soil-pit-sampling">Soil pit sampling</h4>
<ol start="31" type="1">
<li><p>Prepare a soil sample zip-lock bag. Use a permanent marker to
write the plot code, date of collection and soil depth increment. Place
a barcode label on the sample bag, keeping in sequential order.</p></li>
<li><p>Select the <em>horizon</em> from the dropdown list associated
with the first sample. The horizon list is derived from the soil pit
characterisation information entered above under soil pit
characterisation.</p></li>
<li><p>Select the <em>scan barcode</em> button to scan the barcode label
on the sample.</p></li>
<li><p>Collect a 10 cm soil depth 500 g soil sample and place into the
labelled zip-lock bag. Use the pit tape to determine the increments (see
<a href="#soil-samples-1">Additional guidelines</a>).</p></li>
<li><p>Record the <em>upper depth (m) and lower depth (m)</em> of
sample.</p></li>
<li><p>Record any <em>sample comments</em>.</p></li>
<li><p>Save the soil sample and select + button to collect and record
the next sample.</p></li>
<li><p>Repeat steps 31 – 37 for each 10 cm soil depth increment down the
soil profile. Depending on the depth of the horizon, more than one 10 cm
sample can be taken from a horizon. Avoid collecting samples across
horizons.</p></li>
<li><p>Store all samples together in a large plastic bag labelled with
plot code and date of collection.</p></li>
<li><p>To save and review the protocol select <em>Complete soil
observation and pit characterisation</em> then select <em>Edit this
collection</em> to make any changes required.</p></li>
<li><p>If you are collecting bulk density samples, prior to backfilling
the soil pit undertake the <a href="https://linked.data.gov.au/def/nrm/d9e6739a-c2dd-4619-be43-1251449a6436">Soil bulk
density protocol</a>, which collects soil bulk density samples from an
edge of the pit.</p></li>
</ol>"""^^rdf:HTML ;
